I would like to propose a revision to the current reward system, as there appear to be some significant issues with its current implementation. Below, I outline several key areas where improvements are necessary to ensure a fair and effective system.

Verification Process: The current verification process does not adequately confirm whether a vector is genuinely associated with the intended tag. Consequently, miners can exploit this by simply finding vectors with high cosine similarity. For example, the ``np.mean`` of the vector of tags typically yields a score of not less than 0.96. There are other methods as well to achieve high cosine similarity without genuine correlation. I will provide the example score got by unfair way.

Scoring Function: The ``update_score`` function relies on ``rank_scores``, where ``rank_score`` is essentially ``adjusted_score``. This means that penalties, apart from the ``tag_num penalty``, are not factored into the weight settings. As a result, the ``final_score`` serves no substantial purpose beyond being a decorative element.

Validator Efficiency: If the validator employs the OpenAI API and opts for the cost-effective GPT-3.5-turbo model, miners can bypass the need to accurately identify tags. Given that typical conversations encompass no more than a few dozen topics, miners can prepare standard responses to achieve high scores without incurring API costs. Common topic tags include relationships, music, sports, science, love, community, health, wealth, age, adults, memories, entertainment, and others.

In light of these points, I strongly recommend that the foundational code and reward system of the subnet be revised. Such changes are crucial to creating a level playing field and ensuring the integrity of the product.

Our database leverages an endless stream of transcribed podcasts and youtube clips across the entire internet to feed to miners for tagging.

In our subnet code, we take many steps to prevent lookup attacks. Each source feeds in podcasts, news sources, youtube videos, and other types of data that is scraped daily for new episodes/content. This will ensure an ever-evolving, diverse firehose of data that will make lookup attacks virtually impossible.

This change has occurred in the CGP Conversation store, and therefore requires no update to miners or validators.
